marked: To identify the neural correlates for impaired performance on the clock drawing test (CDT) in patients with Alzheimer’s disease (AD), we examined the relationship between the CDT performances and the regional cerebral blood flow (rCBF) in 100 AD patients
Many cognitive skills such as perceptual, executive, motor, and visuospatial ability are necessary for completion of the CDT.

To examine the neural correlates for the CDT deficits in AD, we investigated the relationship between CDT impairment and regional cerebral blood flow (rCBF) measured by single photon emission computed tomography (SPECT

the present study, we examined patients with scores of 3 in the CDT and those with scores less than 3 separately in order to determine whether or not the misrepresentation of the hands and visuospatial disorganization is related to deficit in the distinctive neural network.
A total of 100 patients with probable AD were included
The CDT was administered and scored according to the modified Shulman method

When the patients drew an impaired clock, the patients were instructed to copy, as accurately as possible, a clock from a model, which contained all the numbers on the clock and was set for 25 after 8 (fig. 1).
